{"cursor":"21191","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nA 'misuse of statistics' occurs when a statistical argument asserts a falsehood.\nIn some cases, the misuse may be accidental. In others, it is purposeful and for\nthe gain of the perpetrator. When the statistical reason involved is false or\nmisapplied, this constitutes a 'statistical fallacy'.\n\nThe false statistics trap can be quite damaging to the quest for knowledge.\nFor example, in medical science, correcting a falsehood may take decades and\ncost lives.\n\nMisuses can be easy to fall into. Professional scientists, even mathematicians\nand professional statisticians, can be fooled by even some simple methods, even\nif they are careful to check everything. Scientists have been known to fool\nthemselves with statistics due to lack of knowledge of probability theory and\nlack of standardization of their tests.\n","linknr":211,"url":"Data_manipulation","recorded":1362574559,"links":19,"instances":[],"pdf":[],"categories":["Misuse of statistics|","Laymen and statistics","Ethics and statistics"],"headings":["Types of misuse","See also","References","Further reading","Notes"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a4/Text_document_with_red_question_mark.svg/40px-Text_document_with_red_question_mark.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/d/d/9dd4e461268c8034f5c8564e155c67a6.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/d/c/f/dcfecf8f67da17150a4afbc44e97b461.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/c/5/7c5081abe6c2100f0e44396b6ac51661.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/c/5/7c5081abe6c2100f0e44396b6ac51661.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/a/6/ea669d9b37c9834cbf336659951fe60d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/c/5/7c5081abe6c2100f0e44396b6ac51661.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/c/5/7c5081abe6c2100f0e44396b6ac51661.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/a/6/ea669d9b37c9834cbf336659951fe60d.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/c/5/7c5081abe6c2100f0e44396b6ac51661.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/